title: For Sale:  SAR-1 AK with scope
postcontent:
What we have is a vintage 2002 Romanian SAR-1 rifle in 7.62 x 39, among the last of the pistol grip AKs made in a military arsenal and imported into these United States.

The rifle came with a side scope mount, and is equipped with a POSP 4x24 scope.
This is a no-zero scope mount. Dial it in once and you can remove it from the rifle for close in work or if you just wish a lighter package, and slide it back on as needed and it will be on target.
The scope is the good version made in Belarus, with a red LED instead of a bulb to illuminate the reticle and it takes a standard American AA battery. Some of these scopes use small bulbs instead of LEDs and take odd-ball Soviet batteries.
This scope was designed just for the 7.62 x 39 and the AK, and has a choke range finder for out to 400 meters, and three aiming chevrons, for 100 meters, 200 meters and 300 meters. Zero it at 100 meters and your good to go out to 300 meters!
The illuminated reticle allows one to engage targets in low light conditions where one would normally be unable to see the rifle sights. Even in total darkness you can engage your target if it is at all illuminated, such as sitting around a camp fire, inside an illuminated building or car while you are concealed safely in total darkness, and even without e battery it is still a fully useful telescopic sight.
http://kalinkaoptics.com/posp-4x24-r...k-version.html

The length of pull was too short for comfortable use with the scope, and so rather than scrunch up uncomfortably every time it was used the stock was lengthened.
Now the rifle shoulders comfortably and the scope comes on target fast every time.
The butt was extended by inserting an oak spacer, secured with epoxy and screws. The mil-spec metal butt plate was retained as well as the butt trap to store the tool kit. This butt is as strong as ever.
The rear sling swivel was also moved to the side of the butt which carries the rifle much more comfortably and contently, either across the back or in front of the chest. 

This is a great combo and you won't be disappointed.  Mor pix available, just reply to email.

title: For Sale/Trade:  *FFL EXEMPT* sniper rifle - one of the last truly free guns!
postcontent:
You read that correctly... the gun I have listed below is NOT considered a firearm and is exempt from the provisions of the National Firearms Act of 1934 as amended by the Gun Control Act of 1968. It has a receiver that was ACTUALLY made prior to 1899, the cut off date for antique firearms. This is different than curio/relic status. As an exempt antique, this gun requires no FFL to ship it directly to or from your door or to anyone else in nearly any other state. This gun has never been on the books and never will be (unless an act of Congress changes the current law). In fact, an FFL can actually get into paperwork trouble with the ATF should they log it in their bound books. (For more information, please see http://www.rawles.to/Pre-1899_FAQ.html)

This is an 1891 Argentine contract Mauser, manufactured by Ludwig Loewe in Berlin. The rifle is chambered in a powerful 7.65 x 53 ARG caliber (also known as 7.65 Argentine). The rifle has an interesting history, based on certain clues the rifle bears. The rifle has an engraved steel butt plate, with the initials "RLT" and the date 27, 8, '42 (August 27th 1942) in the European date format, indicating the rifle was likely brought into the US some time after the US entrance into WWII (it has no import marks). Secondly, the rifle was converted from its original configuration to its present state in the late 30's to early 40's as evidenced by the type of resin used to fill the cleaning rod hole in the stock. The rifle was professionally customized by a skilled gunsmith, who cut down the barrel and re-crowned it, added a new front sight, turned down the bolt, shortened the stock and re-blued and re-finished the gun. Some time later, the rear sight was removed and the receiver drilled and tapped for a scope mount. The rifle has a 5-round internal magazine and the bolt cocks on closing. The bore and chamber are excellent. This is not some modern hack-job garage project sporter conversion. 

The gun will come as pictured, including a camo rifle bag, sling, 1930's vintage shell holder, a 1942 Swiss ammo pouch and 45 rounds of military surplus non-corrosive ammo (Hornady loads modern production 7.65 ARG high performance ammo). 

Cash price is $450. I will trade flat across for an EOTech holographic weapons sight model 512, 517 or 552 in the traditional black housing. Other firearm trades considered as well.

title: For Sale:  Taurus Tracker .45ACP Revolver
postcontent:
Selling this impossible to find Taurus Tracker 5 shot revolver in 45ACP.
I bought this at a gun show, stuck it in the safe, and never shot it; I'm not much of a  revolver guy, and i'm selling my items i never shoot.
This has the six inch ported barrel and fires a 45 ACP round: don't confuse this with the "judge" which shoots .45 long colt.
the profile is smaller, because the cylinder only holds five rounds, which require the rounds to be placed in the 5 round "moon" clips shown in the photo. Because .45 ACP rounds do not have a rim, they need the rings to hold the rounds in the cylinder.
because it holds an odd number of rounds, there is no "half moon" clips avaialble the way 6 round revolvers might have.
I have all the original packaging for this firearm. Includes everything you see in the picture: 5 moon clips, the original keys, and all packaging materials.
